# Why: Coolify rebuilds the image on every push to main. Without a cache,
#      `npm ci` (the installer stage) re-downloads ~2GB of tarballs from
#      the npm registry every build — adding 60-90s of network I/O even
#      when only application code changed. BuildKit's cache mount feature
#      lets the npm cache directory persist across builds: subsequent
#      `npm ci` runs hit the local cache for unchanged packages and only
#      pull what's actually new in the lockfile.
#
#      Two pieces required:
#        1. `# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1.6` directive at the very top of
#           the Dockerfile to enable BuildKit's `--mount` syntax. Coolify's
#           Docker 29.4.2 + Buildx already supports this; the directive
#           just opts in.
#        2. `RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.npm,sharing=locked npm ci`
#           on the installer stage's npm-ci line.
#
#      `sharing=locked` prevents two parallel builds from corrupting the
#      cache. The cache survives between Coolify deploys on the same
#      build host. First build is no faster (cache empty), subsequent
#      builds with stable lockfile are ~60-90s faster.
#
#      Why only the installer stage and not the runner stage:
#        • The runner stage runs as `USER nodejs` (uid 1001) BEFORE
#          `npm ci --only=production`. Its npm cache lives at
#          /home/nodejs/.npm, not /root/.npm. Adding a cache mount to the
#          runner would need uid=1001,gid=1001 + careful target path
#          adjustments — extra complexity for marginal speedup since the
#          production-only install is already a small subset of installer.
#        • The installer stage's `npm ci` (full devDependencies install
#          for the build pipeline) is the heavy one. Caching it covers
#          ~95% of the win.
#
#      Cache busting (rare): if the cache ever gets poisoned, change the
#      mount `id=` parameter to invalidate (e.g. `id=npm-v2`).
#
#      Fragility: LOW. The change is 2 lines (1 directive at top, 1 mount
#      arg). Upstream may eventually adopt BuildKit cache mounts themselves
#      (it's a popular pattern); when they do, this overlay becomes a
#      conflict-free no-op merge.
#
diff --git a/docker/Dockerfile b/docker/Dockerfile
--- a/docker/Dockerfile
+++ b/docker/Dockerfile
@@ -1,3 +1,4 @@
+# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1.6
 ###########################
 #     BASE CONTAINER      #
 ###########################
@@ -79,7 +80,11 @@ COPY --from=builder /app/lingui.config.ts ./lingui.config.ts
 COPY --from=builder /app/patches ./patches

-RUN npm ci
+# MODIFIED for BizRethink overlay 020: BuildKit cache mount on the npm cache
+# directory. Reuses tarballs across rebuilds, cutting ~60-90s off repeat
+# Coolify deploys when only application code changes (no lockfile churn).
+# sharing=locked prevents concurrent build corruption. See overlays/020.
+RUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.npm,sharing=locked npm ci

 # Then copy all the source code (as it changes more often)
